"""
mkt-christ — Proverbs 7–9 (80 missing verses; ch8:30 already present)
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-proverbs-7-9.py
Ch7: The Strange Woman — foil to Lady Wisdom; the naive man led to Sheol;
  vv1-5 wisdom-inscription → new covenant heart (Jer 31:33; Heb 8:10);
  v22 ox-to-slaughter contrast with Isa 53:7 (willing vs. deceived sacrifice);
  v27 Sheol-road → Christ reverses the death trajectory (John 10:10; Rev 20:14).
Ch8: Lady Wisdom's self-speech — most Christologically dense passage in Proverbs;
  vv1-3 public proclamation → type of Christ calling in the temple courts;
  vv15-16 kings-reign-through-me → Col 1:16-17; vv22-31 pre-existence → Col 1:15;
  John 1:1-3; Heb 1:2; v30 daily delight → Matt 3:17; v31 rejoicing-in-humanity
  → John 1:14 Incarnation; v35 find-me-find-life → John 14:6; 10:10.
Ch9: Wisdom's banquet vs. Folly's counterfeit; vv1-6 feast invitation →
  Matt 22:2-14; John 6:35; Matt 26:26; v10 fear=beginning-of-wisdom → Col 2:3;
  v18 Sheol-guests → Christ's descent and resurrection reversal.
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

PROVERBS = {
  "7": {
    "1": "<p>The theme: the father&#8217;s teaching as the life-preserving word that guards the son. The NT presents Christ as the ultimate teacher whose words preserve life (John 6:63: &#8220;the words I have spoken to you are spirit and life&#8221;). Proverbs&#8217; parental instruction participates in the same pattern — the preserving word that the pupil must internalize — but points beyond itself to the Word made flesh who speaks with authority greater than the father.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The theme: keeping the commandment as the path to life. Jesus identifies himself as the fulfilment of this commandment-keeping: &#8220;If you keep my commands, you will remain in my love&#8221; (John 15:10). The &#8220;apple of your eye&#8221; phrase (the pupil of the eye) connotes what is most precious and most guarded — the commandment as the very thing one guards most carefully. Christ guards his own in the same way (John 17:12).</p>",
    "3": "<p>The inscription on the tablet of the heart anticipates YHWH&#8217;s new covenant promise: &#8220;I will put my law in their minds and write it on their hearts&#8221; (Jer 31:33; Heb 8:10). The father&#8217;s command to inscribe wisdom internally is the shadow of what the Spirit accomplishes in the new covenant. Christ is the mediator of this new covenant (Heb 9:15) whose Spirit writes the law on the heart rather than on stone tablets.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The theme: the intimacy between the learner and wisdom — &#8220;Say to wisdom, you are my sister.&#8221; The sister-language in the ANE was used for intimate covenant relationship (Song of Songs 4:9-10 uses it for the beloved). The invitation to treat wisdom as one&#8217;s most intimate companion anticipates Paul&#8217;s declaration: &#8220;Christ Jesus&#8230; has become for us wisdom from God&#8221; (1 Cor 1:30). Relationship with Christ is the fulfillment of the intimacy with wisdom that Proverbs commends.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The theme: wisdom as the protection against the seductive-stranger who leads to death. In the NT, Christ presents himself as the one who guards his own against the thief who &#8220;comes only to steal and kill and destroy&#8221; (John 10:10). The Strange Woman&#8217;s flattering words are the false invitation; Christ&#8217;s is the true one: &#8220;I have come that they may have life and have it abundantly.&#8221;</p>",
    "6": "<p>The theme: the instructional scene — the observer watching from the window. The narrator&#8217;s observational distance in vv6-23 frames the Strange Woman&#8217;s seduction as something to be seen and understood rather than experienced. Christ&#8217;s role as the one who sees through all appearances (John 2:24-25: &#8220;he knew what was in each person&#8221;) and teaches from that knowledge is the fulfilment of this wisdom-observation posture.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The theme: the naive young man who lacks &#8220;heart&#8221; (sense/wisdom). The NT equivalent is the one who builds on sand rather than rock (Matt 7:26-27): the person who hears the teaching but has not internalized it and so is vulnerable to destruction. Christ&#8217;s description of the foundation-less person uses the same vocabulary of structural vulnerability that Proverbs uses for the naive man.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The theme: the path that leads toward death. The narrative of the naive man &#8220;heading down the road toward her house&#8221; is the paradigm of the wrong path that Proverbs consistently warns against. Christ identifies himself as &#8220;the Way&#8221; (John 14:6) — the path that does not lead to the Strange Woman&#8217;s house but to the Father. The right path and the wrong path are the fundamental binary of the wisdom tradition, and Christ claims to be the right one.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The theme: darkness as the environment of moral danger. The naive man&#8217;s approach &#8220;in the black darkness of night&#8221; echoes Proverbs&#8217; consistent association of darkness with evil and wisdom with light (Prov 4:18-19). John&#8217;s prologue identifies Christ as the Light who shines in the darkness (John 1:4-5). The man who approaches in darkness is the emblem of those who &#8220;loved darkness rather than light because their deeds were evil&#8221; (John 3:19).</p>",
    "10": "<p>A shadow: the Strange Woman &#8220;dressed like a prostitute, her heart scheming&#8221; is the false seducer whose external appearance conceals deadly intent. The contrast with Christ is precise — Christ&#8217;s external appearance (&#8220;no beauty that we should desire him,&#8221; Isa 53:2) conceals life-giving intent. The one who appears attractive leads to death; the one who appeared unimpressive brings life. The reversal is total.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The theme: the Strange Woman&#8217;s restlessness as moral instability. She is &#8220;loud and defiant; her feet never stay at home&#8221; — always seeking the next victim. This contrasts with the Wisdom who calls from a fixed position (8:2-3) and with Christ who says &#8220;come to me, all you who are weary&#8221; (Matt 11:28) — not a predator seeking victims but a host offering rest to those who come.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The theme: the opportunistic lurking of Dame Folly at every corner. The Strange Woman&#8217;s hunting posture — waiting at every corner for the naive — anticipates the NT&#8217;s description of the devil who &#8220;prowls around like a roaring lion looking for someone to devour&#8221; (1 Pet 5:8). The contrast with Christ as the Good Shepherd (John 10:11-14) who seeks the sheep not to devour but to protect is structurally complete.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The theme: the physical aggression of the seductress — &#8220;she grabbed him and kissed him.&#8221; The violation of normal social restraint (she initiates, she grabs) signals the inversion of proper order. In contrast, Christ does not seize but invites: &#8220;Behold, I stand at the door and knock&#8221; (Rev 3:20) — the One who could command instead knocks and waits. The Strange Woman&#8217;s predation is the foil that makes Christ&#8217;s invitation-model conspicuous.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The theme: religion as cover for immorality — the fellowship offering already paid as the pretext for the seduction. Jesus confronts this inversion: those who say &#8220;Lord, Lord&#8221; while practicing lawlessness (Matt 7:21-23). The Strange Woman uses religious obligation as the lure; Christ demands that religious profession match moral reality. The counterfeit religiosity of v14 is precisely what the prophets denounce and what Christ&#8217;s teaching exposes.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The theme: the false search — &#8220;I was looking for you.&#8221; She presents her predatory pursuit as loving seeking. Christ inverts the vocabulary: he is the one who genuinely seeks the lost (Luke 15:4-7: the shepherd who leaves the ninety-nine to seek the one lost sheep). The Strange Woman&#8217;s &#8220;seeking&#8221; leads to death; Christ&#8217;s seeking is to restore life.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The theme: the bed of luxury as the bait. The elaborate preparation — colored blankets, fine Egyptian linen — describes the sensory appeal of the path that leads to death. The contrast with Christ&#8217;s invitation is stark: &#8220;I am the bread of life&#8221; (John 6:35) — the nourishment offered is not sensory luxury but the sustaining reality that outlasts every appetite. The one who eats Wisdom&#8217;s bread never hungers again (John 6:35); the one who consumes the Strange Woman&#8217;s hospitality is consumed.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The theme: the pleasant scents that mask death. The myrrh, aloes, and cinnamon are the signature of the Strange Woman&#8217;s seduction — the aromatic coating on a deadly invitation. In the NT, myrrh appears at both Christ&#8217;s birth (Matt 2:11) and burial (John 19:39-40). The same spices belong to the story of the one who came to give life through death rather than death through pleasure. The aroma is the same; the direction is reversed.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The theme: the invitation to pleasure without commitment or cost. The Strange Woman&#8217;s invitation — &#8220;let us drink our fill of love until morning&#8221; — is the counterfeit of Wisdom&#8217;s invitation in ch9 (&#8220;come and eat my bread&#8221;). Jesus&#8217; invitation is more demanding: &#8220;whoever wants to be my disciple must deny themselves and take up their cross&#8221; (Matt 16:24). The easy pleasure of the Strange Woman&#8217;s invitation is the surface appeal that conceals the road to Sheol (v27).</p>",
    "19": "<p>The theme: the absent husband as the enabler of the seduction. The absence of proper authority creates the space for the counterfeit offer. In contrast, Christ as the present Shepherd knows each sheep by name (John 10:3,14) and is never absent from his own: &#8220;I am with you always, to the end of the age&#8221; (Matt 28:20). The Strange Woman exploits the husband&#8217;s absence; the Good Shepherd&#8217;s permanent presence is the guard against such exploitation.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The theme: the false calculation of impunity. The Strange Woman reassures: &#8220;he will not be back until the full moon&#8221; — the short window of apparent freedom. The wisdom tradition consistently exposes this calculation as the fool&#8217;s error: &#8220;though a sinner does evil a hundred times and lives long, I know that it will be well with those who fear God&#8221; (Eccl 8:12). Christ&#8217;s return (the parousia) is the definitive closing of the window: no one knows the day or hour (Matt 24:36), but it will come.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The theme: the power of flattering speech to overcome rational resistance. The Strange Woman&#8217;s &#8220;many persuasive words&#8221; and &#8220;smooth speech&#8221; function as an anti-gospel: false words that lead to death. Christ&#8217;s words are characterized by their truth and authority — &#8220;the crowds were astonished at his teaching because he taught as one who had authority&#8221; (Matt 7:28-29). The persuasion is contrasted: the Strange Woman persuades to destruction; Christ&#8217;s authority calls to life.</p>",
    "22": "<p>A shadow: the naive man follows &#8220;like an ox heading to slaughter.&#8221; The contrast with Isa 53:7 is pointed: the Servant of the LORD goes to slaughter willingly and redemptively — &#8220;like a sheep before its shearers is silent, so he did not open his mouth.&#8221; The naive man is an unwitting victim of deception; Christ is the knowing, willing sacrifice. The same slaughter-image describes two radically different deaths — one the result of foolish deception, the other the act of saving love.</p>",
    "23": "<p>A shadow: the arrow in the liver, the bird in the snare — sudden, fatal, unexpected. The naive man&#8217;s death is described with hunting imagery (snare, arrow) that the Psalms apply to the wicked&#8217;s fate and the Servant&#8217;s experience of being hunted by enemies. Christ walked knowingly into the snare of his enemies (John 18:4: &#8220;Jesus, knowing all that was going to happen to him, stepped forward&#8221;) — the bird who knows it is a snare and enters it to save those trapped inside.</p>",
    "24": "<p>The theme: the direct address &#8220;my children, listen to me&#8221; — the father-teacher&#8217;s appeal that grounds the moral warning. Jesus uses identical direct address language in John 13:33 (&#8220;my children&#8221;) and Matt 11:28 (&#8220;come to me&#8221;). The pedagogical authority claimed by Wisdom&#8217;s teacher finds its fulfilment in the one who says &#8220;I am the way, the truth, and the life&#8221; — the ultimate teacher who does not merely point to the right path but is it.</p>",
    "25": "<p>The theme: the heart that must not &#8220;wander toward her ways.&#8221; The active guarding of the heart against the wrong direction is the consistent wisdom call that Proverbs 4:23 states as the principle: &#8220;above all else, guard your heart.&#8221; Christ&#8217;s teaching on the heart (Matt 5:28: adultery begins in the heart) internalizes the command. The new covenant provision is the Spirit who guards the heart from within — not merely the external warning not to wander.</p>",
    "26": "<p>A shadow: &#8220;She has brought down many victims; a long line of powerful men have been destroyed by her.&#8221; The Strange Woman&#8217;s destructive power cuts across social status — the powerful are as vulnerable as the naive. The contrast is with Christ whose power is also universal in reach: &#8220;I, when I am lifted up from the earth, will draw all people to myself&#8221; (John 12:32). Both the Strange Woman and Christ draw from all of humanity — but to opposite destinations.</p>",
    "27": "<p>A shadow: &#8220;Her house is the road to Sheol, it leads to the inner chambers of death.&#8221; Sheol as the destination of those who follow Folly points forward to the second death — Death and Hades thrown into the lake of fire (Rev 20:14). Christ&#8217;s resurrection is the decisive reversal of the Sheol-road: by dying and rising, he holds the keys of death and Hades (Rev 1:18). The road to Sheol that the Strange Woman&#8217;s house represents is the road Christ entered, reversed, and exited as its conqueror.</p>"
  },
  "8": {
    "1": "<p>The theme: Wisdom calling out publicly — &#8220;Does wisdom not call out? Does understanding not raise her voice?&#8221; The public proclamation of wisdom in the streets and gates anticipates Christ&#8217;s public teaching. On the last day of the Feast of Tabernacles, Jesus stood in the temple courts and cried out: &#8220;Let anyone who is thirsty come to me and drink&#8221; (John 7:37) — the identical posture of Wisdom calling in public. The call of Wisdom in Proverbs 8 is a type of the public proclamation of Christ.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The theme: Wisdom at the crossroads — the point of decision. The high ground and crossroads position signifies the most public and unavoidable place for the call: everyone who passes the crossroads hears it. Jesus teaches at Passover (John 7), at the well (John 4), by the sea (Mark 1), in the synagogue (Luke 4:16) — always where people gather. The invitation cannot be missed; only the response distinguishes those who receive and those who ignore.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The theme: Wisdom crying at the city gates. The gates were the public gathering place for legal proceedings, commerce, and community life — the most prominent possible location for public address. Jesus&#8217; entry into Jerusalem (Matt 21:1-11), his teaching in the temple courts, and the disciples&#8217; proclamation at Pentecost (Acts 2:1-11 — in the most public space of the city) all follow the same pattern: the wisdom of God declared at the most central point of public life.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The theme: Wisdom&#8217;s universal address — &#8220;I am calling to you — to all humanity, to every child of Adam.&#8221; The scope of the invitation is explicitly universal: not Israel only, not the wise only, but every human being. This universality is taken up directly in Christ&#8217;s mission: &#8220;For God so loved the world&#8221; (John 3:16); &#8220;Go and make disciples of all nations&#8221; (Matt 28:19). The universal call of Wisdom finds its fulfilment in the universal mission of Christ.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The theme: Wisdom addressing the naive and the foolish — the lowest-capacity audience. The call is not to those who already have wisdom but to those who most need it: the naive (<i>pĕtāyîm</i>) and fools (<i>kĕsîlîm</i>). Jesus&#8217; invitations are similarly directed to those considered least worthy: tax collectors, sinners, the poor (Luke 4:18; Matt 11:5). The one whom Wisdom calls is not the elite but the most needy — and Christ calls with the same directional preference.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The theme: Wisdom speaking what is &#8220;excellent&#8221; and &#8220;right.&#8221; The self-testimony of Wisdom — that everything from her mouth is right — is the pattern that Jesus applies to himself with even greater force: &#8220;Heaven and earth will pass away, but my words will never pass away&#8221; (Matt 24:35). Wisdom claims reliability; Christ claims permanence. The words of Wisdom endure because they are the words of the one through whom all things were made (John 1:3).</p>",
    "7": "<p>The theme: Wisdom&#8217;s mouth speaks truth and hates wickedness. The self-description &#8220;my mouth speaks truth; wickedness is detestable to me&#8221; belongs to the same truthfulness-cluster that Jesus applies to himself (John 14:6: &#8220;I am the truth&#8221;; John 18:37: &#8220;everyone on the side of truth listens to me&#8221;). Wisdom&#8217;s truth-claim is not merely epistemological — it is ontological. Christ does not merely speak the truth; he is it.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The theme: Wisdom&#8217;s words as entirely right, nothing twisted or deceptive. The claim that Wisdom speaks nothing crooked (<i>niptāl</i>, twisted/perverse) anticipates the NT&#8217;s description of Christ as &#8220;without sin&#8221; (Heb 4:15) and his teaching as uncorrupted by error. In contrast to the false wisdom of human tradition (Col 2:8: &#8220;hollow and deceptive philosophy&#8221;), the wisdom of God — personified here and embodied in Christ — contains no twisting.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The theme: Wisdom&#8217;s words as &#8220;all clear&#8221; to those who have understanding. The receptivity principle — that Wisdom&#8217;s words are clear to those with knowledge — mirrors Jesus&#8217; teaching on hearing: &#8220;Whoever has ears to hear, let them hear&#8221; (Matt 13:9); &#8220;For whoever has, more will be given&#8221; (Matt 13:12). Understanding is both prerequisite and result. The person who has received wisdom receives more; the person who has closed their ears hears nothing even when Wisdom speaks plainly.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The theme: Wisdom&#8217;s instruction superior to silver; Wisdom&#8217;s knowledge better than the finest gold. The wisdom-over-wealth comparison reaches its fullest expression in Christ: &#8220;In whom are hidden all the treasures of wisdom and knowledge&#8221; (Col 2:3). Not a comparison between wisdom and wealth, but the identification of Christ as the location in which wisdom itself is stored. To gain Christ is to gain more than all the gold that Proverbs&#8217; comparisons could describe.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The theme: Wisdom more valuable than precious gems, nothing comparable. Job 28 extends this comparison into a meditation on wisdom&#8217;s inaccessibility — it cannot be purchased even with gold. The NT answer to Job&#8217;s question (&#8220;where can wisdom be found?&#8221;) is Christ: &#8220;It is because of him that you are in Christ Jesus, who has become for us wisdom from God&#8221; (1 Cor 1:30). The incomparable wisdom of Proverbs 8:11 is found in a person.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The theme: Wisdom living &#8220;alongside prudence&#8221; — the practical wisdom-cluster. The self-description of Wisdom as the source of prudence (<i>ʿormāh</i>), knowledge, and good judgment anticipates Paul&#8217;s description of Christ as the one &#8220;in whom are hidden all the treasures of wisdom and knowledge&#8221; (Col 2:3). Wisdom and its practical companions do not exist as abstract qualities but are located in the divine person who speaks in Proverbs 8.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The theme: the fear of YHWH as hating evil — pride, arrogance, evil conduct, perverse speech. This is the moral content of wisdom&#8217;s self-description: wisdom is not morally neutral but specifically opposed to pride. Jesus&#8217; consistent confrontation of religious pride (the Pharisees, the scribes, the self-righteous) and his beatitude for the poor in spirit (Matt 5:3) enacts the same principle. The hatred of pride that belongs to YHWH&#8217;s wisdom is demonstrated in Christ&#8217;s ministry.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The theme: &#8220;Mine are counsel and tested wisdom; I am understanding; I have strength.&#8221; Wisdom claims the four royal qualities of Isaiah&#8217;s Messianic king: &#8220;The Spirit of the LORD will rest on him — the Spirit of wisdom and understanding, the Spirit of counsel and strength&#8221; (Isa 11:2). The attributes that Wisdom claims for herself are precisely the attributes that Isaiah predicts will rest on the Branch from Jesse — the one whose coming is the fullest embodiment of these qualities.</p>",
    "15": "<p>A revelation of God: &#8220;Through me kings reign and rulers issue just decrees.&#8221; The pre-existent Wisdom through whom all just governance functions is identified in the NT as Christ: &#8220;by him all things were created&#8230; whether thrones or powers or rulers or authorities — all things have been created through him and for him&#8221; (Col 1:16). The governance-through-Wisdom claim of Prov 8:15 is the OT anticipation of the Colossians declaration that all authority structures exist in Christ.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The theme: rulers governing through Wisdom. The extension from kings to princes to all who exercise righteous authority signals that Wisdom&#8217;s governance is comprehensive. In Acts, the early church applies Ps 2:2 (kings of the earth against YHWH and his anointed) to Christ&#8217;s kingship (Acts 4:25-26). The Wisdom through whom earthly rulers govern finds its ultimate expression in the one to whom &#8220;all authority in heaven and on earth has been given&#8221; (Matt 28:18).</p>",
    "17": "<p>A revelation of God: &#8220;I love those who love me; those who seek me earnestly will find me.&#8221; Wisdom&#8217;s promise of mutual love and findability is taken up directly by Jesus: &#8220;Ask and it will be given to you; seek and you will find&#8221; (Matt 7:7-8). The seek-and-find promise of Prov 8:17 is reaffirmed as the governing principle of relationship with Christ. &#8220;I love those who love me&#8221; maps onto John 14:21: &#8220;Whoever loves me will be loved by my Father, and I too will love them.&#8221;</p>",
    "18": "<p>The theme: riches, honor, lasting wealth, and righteousness with Wisdom. The inventory of benefits that come through relationship with Wisdom is not merely material but covenantal: &#8220;lasting wealth&#8221; (<i>hôn ʿātēq</i>) and <i>ṣĕdāqāh</i> (righteousness). In Christ, Paul describes the ultimate exchange: &#8220;Though he was rich, yet for your sake he became poor, so that you through his poverty might become rich&#8221; (2 Cor 8:9). The riches that come through Wisdom are embodied in Christ&#8217;s self-giving.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The theme: Wisdom&#8217;s yield better than fine gold and choice silver — the same comparison as v10-11 but now applied to Wisdom&#8217;s productive output. The agricultural yield-vocabulary (<i>pĕrî</i>, fruit; <i>tĕbûʾāh</i>, produce) anticipates the NT fruit-of-the-Spirit language (Gal 5:22-23) and Jesus&#8217; vine-and-branches discourse (John 15:5: &#8220;whoever remains in me and I in them will bear much fruit&#8221;). The fruit that Wisdom produces is the same fruit that abiding in Christ produces.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The theme: &#8220;I walk in the path of righteousness, along the roads of justice.&#8221; Wisdom&#8217;s self-description as one who walks in righteousness is the pattern that Jesus fulfils as the one who is &#8220;righteous&#8221; (1 Pet 3:18; 1 John 2:1) and who says &#8220;I am the Way&#8221; (John 14:6). The path that Wisdom walks and that she invites others to walk becomes, in Christ, a person to follow rather than a principle to imitate.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The theme: Wisdom giving a real inheritance to those who love her. The inheritance vocabulary (<i>naḥălāh</i>, the ancestral portion allocated by covenant) points to the covenant theology of the land. In the NT, the inheritance is transformed: &#8220;an inheritance that can never perish, spoil or fade&#8221; (1 Pet 1:4); Christ is himself the inheritance (Eph 1:11: &#8220;in him we were also chosen&#8221;). The inheritance that Wisdom&#8217;s lovers receive is the person of Christ — who fills the storehouses of those who receive him.</p>",
    "22": "<p>An allusion: &#8220;The LORD possessed me at the beginning of his way, before the oldest of his works.&#8221; This is the most explicitly pre-existence statement in Proverbs. Paul applies it directly to Christ: &#8220;He is the image of the invisible God, the firstborn over all creation&#8221; (Col 1:15). The &#8220;firstborn&#8221; (<i>prōtotokos</i>) language parallels the Proverbs claim that Wisdom pre-exists all other works. The verse is not a proof text but a directional arrow: the Wisdom who was &#8220;at the beginning&#8221; is the Logos who &#8220;was in the beginning&#8221; (John 1:1).</p>",
    "23": "<p>An allusion: &#8220;I was installed from eternity — from the very beginning, before the earth existed.&#8221; The language of pre-creation existence is taken up in John&#8217;s prologue: &#8220;In the beginning was the Word&#8221; (John 1:1). The Wisdom that pre-exists the earth&#8217;s creation is the Logos who pre-exists all things. Jesus&#8217; own claim &#8220;before Abraham was, I am&#8221; (John 8:58) echoes the same eternal pre-existence that Proverbs 8 describes for Wisdom.</p>",
    "24": "<p>An allusion: &#8220;Before the oceans existed I was born — before the springs were teeming with water.&#8221; Wisdom&#8217;s pre-cosmic existence is anchored to the creation narrative (Gen 1) — she is present before the primordial waters are separated and ordered. The NT claims the same for Christ: &#8220;He is before all things&#8221; (Col 1:17); &#8220;In the beginning was the Word, and the Word was with God&#8221; (John 1:1-2). The &#8220;before everything&#8221; claim of Proverbs 8 is one of the primary OT witnesses the NT draws on for Christ&#8217;s pre-existence.</p>",
    "25": "<p>An allusion: &#8220;Before the mountains were in place, before the hills, I was brought into being.&#8221; The mountains as the oldest created structures in ancient Near Eastern cosmology (Ps 90:2: &#8220;before the mountains were born&#8221;) mark the ultimate antiquity; Wisdom precedes them. The NT applies this antiquity-claim to Christ through the Logos prologue: &#8220;All things were made through him, and without him nothing was made&#8221; (John 1:3) — the maker necessarily precedes the made.</p>",
    "26": "<p>An allusion: &#8220;Before he had made the earth or its open lands or the first dust of the world&#8221; — the pre-creation horizon that Wisdom inhabits. Hebrews&#8217; claim that the Son is &#8220;the radiance of God&#8217;s glory and the exact representation of his being, sustaining all things by his powerful word&#8221; (Heb 1:3) assumes this pre-cosmic relationship. The Son who sustains all things from before creation is the Wisdom who was present before the first dust of the world.</p>",
    "27": "<p>An allusion: &#8220;When he set the heavens in place I was there.&#8221; Wisdom as eyewitness to the creation act. John&#8217;s prologue makes the identical claim from the other direction: &#8220;All things were made through him, and without him nothing was made that has been made&#8221; (John 1:3). Hebrews adds the functional claim: God &#8220;made the universe through&#8221; the Son (Heb 1:2). Wisdom as present-at-creation becomes, in Christ, the agent-of-creation.</p>",
    "28": "<p>The theme: Wisdom present at the fixing of clouds and fountains — the ordering of the cosmos. The cosmic ordering activity that Wisdom witnesses and participates in is the same activity attributed to Christ in Col 1:17: &#8220;in him all things hold together.&#8221; The present tense of Col 1:17 is crucial: not merely that Christ created, but that he sustains the cosmic order described in Proverbs 8&#8217;s creation survey. Wisdom watches the ordering; Christ maintains it.</p>",
    "29": "<p>An allusion: Wisdom present when YHWH &#8220;marked out the earth&#8217;s foundations&#8221; — the technical language of the divine architect establishing creation&#8217;s parameters. Hebrews 1:10 (citing Ps 102:25) applies this architect language directly to Christ: &#8220;In the beginning, Lord, you laid the foundations of the earth.&#8221; The Wisdom who witnesses the foundation-laying in Proverbs 8 is the Son identified in Hebrews as the one who laid them.</p>",
    "31": "<p>A shadow: &#8220;Rejoicing in the world he had made, and my delight was in the children of humanity.&#8221; Wisdom&#8217;s delight in the human family is the OT foreshadowing of the Incarnation — the eternal Wisdom taking up residence among the people she delights in. John 1:14: &#8220;the Word became flesh and made his dwelling among us.&#8221; The delight that Wisdom expresses in eternity (v31) is enacted historically when the Wisdom-made-flesh (John 1:14; 1 Cor 1:24) tabernacles with the humanity she rejoices in.</p>",
    "32": "<p>The theme: &#8220;Blessed are those who keep to my ways.&#8221; Wisdom&#8217;s beatitude (<i>ʾašrê</i>) at the opening of her application section (vv32-36) parallels the beatitude-form used by Jesus in the Sermon on the Mount (Matt 5:3-11). Both Wisdom and Christ open their ethical teaching with a declaration of blessing on those who follow the right path. The &#8220;blessed are those&#8221; formula moves from Proverbs through the Psalms to its fullest expression in Christ&#8217;s kingdom proclamation.</p>",
    "33": "<p>The theme: &#8220;Accept instruction and be wise; do not reject it.&#8221; Wisdom&#8217;s appeal to receive instruction and not reject it is the OT register for the NT&#8217;s warning against hardening the heart: &#8220;Today, if you hear his voice, do not harden your hearts&#8221; (Heb 3:7-8, citing Ps 95:7-8). The rejection of Wisdom&#8217;s instruction in Proverbs is the anticipation of the rejection of Christ: &#8220;he came to his own, and his own did not receive him&#8221; (John 1:11).</p>",
    "34": "<p>The theme: &#8220;Blessed is the person who listens to me — waiting at my doors every morning.&#8221; The daily, attentive seeking described here — waiting at Wisdom&#8217;s threshold every morning — anticipates the posture of discipleship. Jesus commends the same daily attentiveness: &#8220;Whoever wants to be my disciple must deny themselves and take up their cross daily and follow me&#8221; (Luke 9:23). The every-morning waiting at Wisdom&#8217;s door is the OT form of the daily cross-bearing of discipleship.</p>",
    "35": "<p>An allusion: &#8220;Whoever finds me finds life and receives the LORD&#8217;s favor.&#8221; Jesus applies this Wisdom-formula to himself directly: &#8220;I am the way, the truth, and the life. No one comes to the Father except through me&#8221; (John 14:6); &#8220;I have come that they may have life, and have it to the full&#8221; (John 10:10). Finding Wisdom = finding life; finding Christ = finding life. The identification of Christ with Wisdom (1 Cor 1:24,30) makes these claims structurally identical: the Wisdom of Prov 8:35 is the same life-source as the Christ of John 14:6.</p>",
    "36": "<p>A shadow: &#8220;But whoever fails to find me harms himself; all who hate me embrace death.&#8221; The anti-beatitude: the one who misses Wisdom enters a death-trajectory. Jesus states the equivalent in John 3:18-19: &#8220;Whoever does not believe is condemned already&#8230; people loved darkness rather than light.&#8221; Rejection of Wisdom = embracing death; rejection of Christ = judgment already fallen. The same trajectory is named in both — and Christ identifies himself as the Wisdom that v36 describes.</p>"
  },
  "9": {
    "1": "<p>A shadow: &#8220;Wisdom has built her house; she has hewn out her seven pillars.&#8221; The house with seven pillars is the architectural preparation for the banquet invitation that follows. The seven pillars are both numerologically complete (seven = fullness) and architecturally grand. In the NT, Christ speaks of preparing a place: &#8220;In my Father&#8217;s house are many rooms; I am going there to prepare a place for you&#8221; (John 14:2). Wisdom&#8217;s house-preparation is the shadow of the divine hospitality that Christ prepares.</p>",
    "2": "<p>A shadow: Wisdom slaughtering animals, mixing wine, and setting the table — the preparation of a royal feast. Jesus&#8217; Parable of the Wedding Banquet (Matt 22:2-14) follows this exact pattern: feast prepared, servants sent, invitation issued. Both describe the same structure of divine invitation: the host prepares everything before the guests arrive; the call goes out before the need is felt. Wisdom&#8217;s feast preparation is the OT archetype of which Christ&#8217;s parables of divine hospitality are the application.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The theme: Wisdom sending servants to call from the heights of the city. The dispatch of messengers with the invitation follows the pattern of the wedding banquet parables (Matt 22:3-4: &#8220;he sent his servants to call those who had been invited&#8221;). In the NT&#8217;s application, the servants are the prophets and apostles; Christ is the host who has already prepared the feast. The calling-from-the-heights posture of Wisdom&#8217;s servants mirrors the prophetic proclamation of the gospel &#8220;from the mountaintops&#8221; (Isa 52:7).</p>",
    "4": "<p>The theme: the invitation directed to the simple — &#8220;Let the simple come in here.&#8221; The call of Wisdom is to those who most need her, not those who already have wisdom. Jesus&#8217; beatitude &#8220;blessed are the poor in spirit&#8221; (Matt 5:3) and his invitation &#8220;come to me, all you who are weary and burdened&#8221; (Matt 11:28) are directed to the same audience: those who know their need. The naive who accepts Wisdom&#8217;s invitation receives what the self-sufficient refuse.</p>",
    "5": "<p>An allusion: &#8220;Come and eat my bread; drink the wine I have mixed.&#8221; Wisdom&#8217;s bread-and-wine invitation is the OT register for Jesus&#8217; &#8220;I am the bread of life; whoever comes to me will never go hungry&#8221; (John 6:35). And at the Last Supper, Jesus takes bread and wine as his body and blood (Matt 26:26-28; 1 Cor 11:23-26) — claiming to be the host of the Wisdom banquet that Proverbs 9 describes. The feast that Wisdom prepares is the feast that Christ embodies and distributes.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The theme: &#8220;Leave your simple ways and live.&#8221; Wisdom&#8217;s call requires a departure — abandoning the path of naivety — as the condition for receiving life. Jesus&#8217; call to discipleship has the same structure: &#8220;If anyone wants to come after me, let them deny themselves, take up their cross, and follow me&#8221; (Matt 16:24). The &#8220;leaving&#8221; that Wisdom calls for is the structure of repentance that Christ&#8217;s call embodies — turn from the old way, walk in the new.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The theme: the rebuke of a mocker brings harm; correcting the wicked earns hurt. This observation about the social cost of truthful correction anticipates the prophets&#8217; experience and Christ&#8217;s: &#8220;Jerusalem, Jerusalem, you who kill the prophets and stone those sent to you&#8221; (Matt 23:37). The wisdom teacher who rebukes mockers suffers for it; Christ&#8217;s truthful confrontation of religious leaders led to his crucifixion. The social logic of mocked-rebuke runs from Proverbs through the passion narrative.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The theme: &#8220;Do not rebuke a mocker or he will only hate you; rebuke a wise person and he will love you.&#8221; The receptivity divide — mocker versus wise person — maps onto the NT&#8217;s division between those who receive Christ&#8217;s teaching and those who reject it. &#8220;The message of the cross is foolishness to those who are perishing, but to us who are being saved it is the power of God&#8221; (1 Cor 1:18). The rebuke of the gospel is hated by the mocker; it is life to the wise who receives it.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The theme: &#8220;Teach the wise and they grow wiser still; instruct the righteous and they gain more.&#8221; The growth principle — wisdom builds on wisdom — is the OT articulation of the NT&#8217;s principle of abiding: &#8220;Whoever has will be given more, and they will have an abundance&#8221; (Matt 13:12). The person already in relationship with Wisdom (or with Christ) receives additional understanding; the one who rejects the initial gift loses what little they have. Receptivity creates a virtuous cycle of increasing wisdom.</p>",
    "10": "<p>An allusion: &#8220;The fear of the LORD is the beginning of wisdom; knowing the Holy One is understanding.&#8221; The thesis of the book restated at its structural midpoint. Paul declares the fulfilment: &#8220;In Christ are hidden all the treasures of wisdom and knowledge&#8221; (Col 2:3). The beginning of wisdom (fear of YHWH) and the fullness of wisdom (Christ) are not opposed but continuous: the reverence for the God who is revealed in Christ is both the starting point and the goal. Knowing &#8220;the Holy One&#8221; (<i>qĕdōšîm</i>) — the divine plural — is understanding; and &#8220;the Holy One of God&#8221; is the title the demoniacs give Jesus (Mark 1:24).</p>",
    "11": "<p>The theme: through Wisdom &#8220;your days will multiply and years will be added to your life.&#8221; The life-prolonging promise of wisdom finds its ultimate expression in Christ&#8217;s gift of eternal life: &#8220;I give them eternal life, and they shall never perish&#8221; (John 10:28). Proverbs&#8217; promise is temporal extension; Christ&#8217;s promise is eternal inclusion. The addition of years that Wisdom promises is the shadow of the eternal life that Christ gives — the same direction, infinitely extended.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The theme: &#8220;If you are wise, the benefit is yours alone; if you scoff, you alone bear the consequences.&#8221; The personal responsibility for receiving or rejecting wisdom is stated sharply here. The NT sharpens it further: &#8220;whoever believes in the Son has eternal life, but whoever rejects the Son will not see life, for God&#8217;s wrath remains on them&#8221; (John 3:36). Individual response to Wisdom — to Christ — has individual eternal consequences that cannot be transferred. The wisdom benefit is personal; so is the judgment for scoffing.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The theme: Dame Folly as the counterfeit host. Folly&#8217;s description — &#8220;loud, naive, and knows nothing&#8221; — is the anti-wisdom figure whose invitation mimics Wisdom&#8217;s but leads to opposite consequences. In the NT, false prophets and false Christs perform the same function: &#8220;They will say, &#8216;Here is the Messiah!&#8217; or &#8216;There he is!&#8217; — do not believe it&#8221; (Matt 24:23). The loud, empty, counterfeit invitation of Dame Folly is the OT archetype of every false alternative to genuine Wisdom.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The theme: Folly at the door of her house at the city&#8217;s high places. The high-place location — the same prominent position from which Wisdom calls (8:2-3) — shows that Folly uses Wisdom&#8217;s methods: public visibility, strategic placement, the rhetoric of invitation. The false prophet&#8217;s location in the midst of the assembly (Jer 23:11: &#8220;both prophet and priest are godless&#8221;) replicates this — using the same institutional platform as genuine prophecy for counterfeit proclamation.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The theme: Folly calling out to those &#8220;going straight on their way.&#8221; The target of Folly&#8217;s invitation is the person who was not seeking Folly — those who were walking on the right path. The NT equivalent is the warning about false teaching that comes to those within the community of faith: &#8220;I am astonished that you are so quickly deserting the one who called you&#8221; (Gal 1:6). The most dangerous counterfeit is not offered to those already lost but to those on the right road.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The theme: Folly&#8217;s invitation using Wisdom&#8217;s words. The identical phrasing (v4 = v16: &#8220;Let the simple come in here&#8221;) demonstrates Folly&#8217;s imitative strategy. The false gospel that Paul confronts in Galatians uses the same vocabulary as the true gospel while reversing its content — &#8220;a different gospel, which is really no gospel at all&#8221; (Gal 1:6-7). The counterfeit invitation sounds like the genuine one; only what follows distinguishes them.</p>",
    "17": "<p>A shadow: &#8220;Stolen water is sweet, and food eaten in secret is delicious.&#8221; Folly&#8217;s appeal is to the pleasure of transgression — the specific pleasure of what is forbidden. This is the appeal that the serpent uses in Eden (&#8220;God knows that when you eat it your eyes will be opened,&#8221; Gen 3:5) and that Satan uses in the wilderness temptations of Jesus (Matt 4:1-11). Christ resists the appeal of the forbidden pleasure; the naive in Proverbs 9 succumbs to it. The stolen-water pleasure is sweet until the swallower discovers where Folly&#8217;s guests end up.</p>",
    "18": "<p>A shadow: &#8220;But he does not know that the dead are there — that her guests are in the depths of Sheol.&#8221; Folly&#8217;s feast ends in Sheol; Wisdom&#8217;s feast ends in life. The eschatological antithesis is the Marriage Supper of the Lamb (Rev 19:9): &#8220;Blessed are those who are invited to the marriage supper of the Lamb.&#8221; The guests at Folly&#8217;s table descend to Sheol; the guests at Wisdom&#8217;s — at Christ&#8217;s — table are the church clothed in righteousness at the final feast. The two invitations of Proverbs 9 find their ultimate resolution in this contrast between the Lamb&#8217;s supper and the second death.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    c = load_comm('mkt-christ', 'proverbs')
    merge_comm(c, PROVERBS)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', 'proverbs', c)
    total = sum(len(vs) for vs in PROVERBS.values())
    print(f'proverbs mkt-christ: {total} entries written (ch7-9)')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
